description: Come Celebrate Hispanic Heritage Month with an evening of rhythm, flavor, and fun! Join us on Wednesday, October 1, from 5:30–7:00 PM at the Kathleen Ludwig Center for Salsa Dance & Dinner Night. Kick off the evening with a lively salsa dance class, no experience needed, just bring your energy and comfy clothes! After dancing, enjoy a delicious dinner together as we honor the richness of Hispanic culture through music, movement, and community. In partnership with Douglass Women in Science & Engineering (WiSE), the event will also feature The Science of the Scent. Led by Magy Georges, Assistant Dean of WiSE, this interactive activity will explore how fragrance is created, how it connects to memory and identity, and how scents from Latin America such as vanilla, cacao, coffee, and citrus have shaped both culture and science. Participants will even get the chance to craft and take home their own unique scent!
name: Salsa Dance & Dinner Night

description: Join us for a Book Talk with Professor Andrés Mario Zervigón!   Wednesday, October 15, 2025, 5.30 – 7.00 PM Art History Graduate Student Lounge, Vorhees Hall, 71 Hamilton Street, New Brunswick   Print Matters: Media and Modernity in Illustrated Magazines, 1910–1970Edited by Maria Antonella Pelizzari and Andrés Mario Zervigón Available November 2025 In the early to mid-twentieth century, the vast majority of printed photographs appeared in the pages of illustrated magazines. Publications such as Life, China Pictorial, Drum, Picture Post, and Ebony shaped public perception and mass media consensus like the Internet does today, bringing a shared visual experience to homes and newsstands around the world. The essays in this volume delve into the technologies and visual strategies behind these publications, showing how their layouts were affected by political, commercial, editorial, and artistic factors leading up to World War II. Featuring over 150 images, Print Matters traces how illustrated magazines evolved across countries and continents, offering new insights into their history and enduring impact on culture and society.   Andrés Mario Zervigón is a professor of the history of photography in the Department of Art History at Rutgers, the State University of New Jersey.
name: Book Talk: Print Matters: Media and Modernity in Illustrated Magazines, 1910–1970 - Andrés Zervigón

description: RU looking to enhance your Rutgers experience with social, academic, professional, and personal experiences to build your leadership and support network? Still looking to find your community within Rutgers? Douglass Residential College provides unique events and opportunities through hands-on research, student organizations, paid experiences, and free travel! By adding a feminist lens to your education, Douglass inspires you to examine inequality, center women’s lived experience in your exploration of the world, and embolden women’s leadership.
